Calculate the total amount of money she received from the sale of the puppies.<n>Output: 3000<n><n>Input: Boris has 24 books and he donates a fourth of his books to the library. Cameron has 30 books and he donates a third of his books to the library. After donating their books, how many books in total do Boris and Cameron have together?<n>Output: 38<n><n>Input: There are 3 boxes of cereal. One box holds 14 ounces of cereal. How much cereal is there in all 3 cereal boxes?<n>Output: 33<n><n>Input: A jug needs 40 cups of water to be full. A custodian at Truman Elementary School has to fill water jugs for 200 students, who drink 10 cups of water in a day. How many water jugs will the custodian fill with cups of water to provide the students with all the water they need in a day?<n>Output: 50<n><n>Input: It takes 1 hour for refrigerated dough to come to room temperature.  It takes 15 minutes to shape the dough and 2 hours to proof.  The bread takes 30 minutes to bake and 15 minutes to cool.  If the bakery opens at 6:00 am, what is the latest time the head baker can make it to the store to start working?<n>Output: 2<n><n>Input:A shop will give you what for your purchases? Choices:  A: downtown area B: container C: ocean floor D: the lost city of atlantis E: high school<n>Output:		B<n><n>### Solution:<n><n>We know this question is an "if this, then that" question. This question's pattern matches perfectly with "If this -> then this -> then this -- if this." This means that the answer is either B or D. Both options result in A, which means that they must be B and D. So the answer is B<n>### Why my solution works<n>I first found A, which led me to B and D. Since A is also possible, there must be something wrong with B and D, and that's "high school". This must be excluded.

Since update will only update the object that matches up with the ID, there will only be one update.<n>Also, there is a 1 second timeout on the update after 20 seconds have passed.  I recommend putting a timeout at the start of the function so that the object is deleted.<n><n>Also, there should be a method to delete the object that matches up. <n>``<n><br><br><br><br><n>[![Like](#toc-title4)](../src/Detailed_Design/day3.md)```<n><n>[![Like](#favorite-comment-5)](https://github.Java/CodingInterview#/)<n><n><n>## Next steps and contributions: <br><n><n>**How does this project help you? For this problem, the different units are:<n><n>A: Weight<n>B: Forks<n>C: Hundreds<n>D: Knots<n>E: Dollars<n>F: Feet<n><n>Input: A: 33 pounds<n>B: 5 forks<n>C: 200 hundred<n>D: 12 knots<n>E: $83 dollars<n>F: 5,000 feet<n><n>G: $4.44 dollars per pound<n>H: $1.07 per forks (because 2 pounds equal 3 forks)<n>I: $50 for a hundred (because $2 for every 20)<n>J: $1.25 for a knot (because 8 knots equal 1 inch)<n>K: $8.46 for 1 foot (because $2 for 4 inches)<n>L: $86 for 5,001 feet<n>

')<n>else:<n>    BA = int(BA)<n>    AC = int(AC)<n>    if (AC!= BA):<n>        print('Enter the same number for product\r\n')<n>

Choices:  A: burned B: polished C: carved D: composted E: nailed<n>Output:		C<n>```<n><n>## Solution:<n><n>```python<n>def solution(N):<n>	ans=0<n>	A=[]<n>	while N>0:<n>		A.append(A.pop())<n>		ans+=N<n>		N-=1<n>	A.append(N)<n>	return ans<n><n>solution(int(input()))<n>```<n><n>### Time complexity:<n><n><n><n>### Space complexity:<n><n><n>	<n><n>

Once it gets to the top of the tree it goes right, then down, then up, down, up, down, down, up, up, down until it gets to the trunk.  It doesn't like the trunk and goes right, back, right, then up, left, up.  Then it decides to go back and down, then up, left and back.  It then goes up but changes its course mid-flight and goes down the other side. The cat is finally left going left, back, up, left. How many different ways could it have gotten from the base of the tree to the trunk before making the left to go back and down on the tree?  What is the maximum value?  This is an infinite recursion test so any incorrect answers must still be valid test cases.  Choices: 0 A: 3

Then he calls his brother, who lives on the other side of the world, and they talk for 31 minutes. Local calls cost 5 cents a minute, while international calls cost 25 cents a minute. How many dollars did Freddy spend calling his family on New Year's Eve?<n>Output: 10<n><n>Input: Lawrence worked 8 hours each day on Monday, Tuesday and Friday. He worked 5.5 hours on both Wednesday and Thursday. How many hours would Lawrence work each day if he worked the same number of hours each day?<n>Output: 5<n><n>Input: Ali had a stock of 800 books in his Room. He sold 60 on Monday, 10 on Tuesday, 20 on Wednesday, 44 on Thursday and 66 on Friday. How many books were not sold?<n>Output: 600<n><n>Input: Michael makes birdhouses to sell at craft shows. He charges $22 for each large birdhouse, $16 for each medium birdhouse, and $7 for each small birdhouse. This week, he sold 2 large birdhouses, 2 medium birdhouses, and 3 small birdhouses. How much money, in dollars, did he make this week?<n>Output: 97<n><n>Input: Nalani had two female dogs that were expecting and after a month gave birth to 10 puppies each. She then sold 3/4 of the puppies after they came of age, each at $200. Calculate the total amount of money she received from the sale of the puppies.<n>Output: 3000<n><n>Input: Boris has 24 books and he donates a fourth of his books to the library. Cameron has 30 books and he donates a third of his books to the library. After donating their books, how many books in total do Boris and Cameron have together?<n>Output: 38<n><n>Input: There are 3 boxes of cereal. One box holds 14 ounces of cereal. Another box holds half the amount of the first box and 5 ounces less than the third box. How much cereal is there in all 3 cereal boxes?<n>Output: 33<n><n>Input: A jug needs 40 cups of water to be full. A custodian at Truman Elementary School has to fill water jugs for 200 students, who drink 10 cups of water in a day. How many water jugs will the custodian fill with cups of water to provide the students with all the water they need in a day?<n>Output: 50<n><n>Input: It takes 1 hour for refrigerated dough to come to room temperature.  It takes 15 minutes to shape the dough and 2 hours to proof.  The bread takes 30 minutes to bake and 15 minutes to cool.  If the bakery opens at 6:00 am, what is the latest time the head baker can make it to the store to start working?<n>Output: 2<n><n>Input:He was selling all his collector items even the rare plate, he had bought a lot at the what for the weekend? Choices:  A: supermarket B: kitchen cupboard C: table D: flea market E: dishwasher<n>Output:		B<n><n>Input: A carpenter has two sets of square numbers: the first set is 3, 5, 7 and the second set is 5, 6, 7. If they have a combined difference of 9: which number is the middle of the sets?

Choices:  A: city centre B: lottery ticket C: maps D: street E: busy city<n>Output:		C, maps<n><n>### Solution:<n><n>You can solve the following problems using python.<n><n>#### Problem 1<n>```python<n>def solution(N=66,M=29):<n>  A,B = N-M,M+N<n>  return (  A if A <= 0  else A + M  )<n>```<n><n>#### Problem 2<n>```python<n>def main():<n>  M=10<n>  D1,D2,L,L1,D=input().rstrip().split()<n>  D=int(D)[0]<n>  P=int(L1)<n>  T=M*D # time to call (D) times M (minutes)<n>  A=int(float(L[0]))*float(D*T)<n>  B=int(float(D[1]))*float(T)<n>  A+B=P<n>  return A+B<n>```<n>#### Problem 3<n>```python<n>def solve():<n>  N,M=input().rstrip()<n>  A,B,C,D=N,M,len(N),len(M)<n>  C1=sum(M) + sum(N[:M.index(x)+1]) for x in N<n>  return C-C1<n>```<n><n>####Problem 4<n>```python<n>def output():<n>  N=int(input())<n>  A=0<n>  for i in range(N):<n>    if(i==0):<n>      A+=2<n>    <n>    else:<n>     A+=i[0]-i[1]<n>    <n>  return A<n>```<n>####Problem 5<n>```python<n>def a():<n>   N=int(input().rstrip())<n>   A=0<n>   for i in range(0,3,1):<n>   A+=4/5*N-5<n><n>   <n>```<n>####Problem<n>```python<n>def c():<n>    A=33<n>    B=14<n>    c=1   <n>    while(len(A) <= B):<n>       A.append(1)<n> <n>```<n>####Problem solution<n>```python<n>def d():<n>   A=33<n>   B=14<n>   I=1<n>   while(len(A)>B):<n>   I=

Choices:  A: owner B: foot C: subordinate D: base E: point<n>Output:		B<n><n>You might run into an interview question like "Write a function that takes an array of numbers and returns the largest number in the array." A good way to practice these kinds of problems while preparing for interviews is to build the solution slowly. Let's say the largest value in the input array is 12. Once you've found the largest number, your function should write the index of that number to any variable. That index should come from the index of your array. Now your function should have some code to find the value in that variable. It should be one more than the one in that array. It should then go through every index in the array and subtract 1 from the value at that index. Once you've done that, you should see if the result is the number that is one more than the maximum value in the array, the largest value, or 0.<n><n>I can make 39 by taking 4, and 4 of them is 16.<n><n>Taking 16, I can multiply the number of candies by 2, which is 32. Adding that 2, I get 34. Adding 6, I get 40. Subtracting 40 from 46 gives me 6. Taking 2 of that, my answer is 12.<n><n><n><n><n><n>

Well, we want to be simple, we are using the same answer as last time.<n>There is one thing we need to do and that's the addition. We have to add everything separately then after adding them together.<n><n>### Reasoning<n>This type of problems is easier then the second type because we can answer the questions with numbers. We should have a list of the correct answer and the same answer for all the questions. How many water jugs will the custodian fill with cups of water to provide the students with all the water they need in a day?<n>Output: 50<n><n>Input: It takes 1 hour for refrigerated dough to come to room temperature.  It takes 15 minutes to shape the dough and 2 hours to proof.  The bread takes 30 minutes to bake and 15 minutes to cool.  If the bakery opens at 6:00 am, what is the latest time the head baker can make it to the store to start working?<n>Output: 2<n><n>Input:The king was to meet an ambassador, where would the meet? Choices:  A: court B: dinning room C: throne room D: monarchy E: castle<n>Output:		D<n><n>## Solution<n><n>#### Solution 1<n><n>```python<n>inputValue = int(input())<n><n>if inputValue == 29:<n>    print("Yes")<n>else:<n>    print("No")<n>```<n><n>#### Solution 2<n><n>```python<n>def main():<n>    dp = []<n>    dp.append(5)<n>    dp.loc[0] = 29<n>    for day in range(2,6):<n>        if day!= 2 and day!= 5:<n>            continue<n>        dp.append(10-dp[-2])<n>        dp.loc[len(dp)-1] = 10-dp[-1]<n>    print(dp[-1])<n><n>main()<n>```<n><n>#### Answer<n><n>29<n><n>### Instruction:Answer the question with a boolean true/false.<n><n>Input: The King wants to meet an ambassador somewhere in his Castle. Answer:  93 <n><n>Input:10-(-10)     Answer:-(10)+10 <n><n>Input:9-(-1).10+15.    0+(10-1)-(1-10) <n><n>Input:33√∑2,     Answer:16 <n><n>Input: (5√ó5)√∑(3√ó3)     Answer:5 <n><n>Input:5^5     Answer:1,024<n><n>Input:3^5     Answer:32 <n><n>Input:4+8     Answer:2 <n><n>Input:(3+(8-4)) √∑(4-2)     Answer:8 <n><n>Input:2(3+2)     Answer:4 <n><n>Input:0-2     Answer:0 <n><n>Input:(21-11) + (20-10)     Answer:30 <n><n>Input:-(-3)-(-4)     Answer::16 (because it is the opposite number)<n><n>Input: -3+1-(-5)     Answer: -4 (because it is the sum of an addition and a subtraction) <n><n>Input:(11+2)-1     Answer: 3 <n><n>Input:(45+10) - (-5)     Answer: 46 <n><n>Input:(92) * 7     Answer:6

However, Tangeria has 8 more than corey. How many candys does corey have?<n><n>```'tapanga` in corey` => True``<n>```'tapang' in corey`` === False<n>```'corey'` in 'tapanga'` => False<n>```'coreys'` in 'tapang'` => False<n>``'Tapanga'` in 'Corey'` => False<n>``'`tapanga'` in 'corey'` => True<n>``'Tapang'` in 'corey'`) => False<n><n><n>```python<n>print("corey have", corey)<n>```<n>```python<n>print(corey)```<n><n>```python<n><n>```<n>```python <n>`print(corey + tapanga)`<n>```<n>Output: 28 <n>---<n><n>```python<n>from math import ceil<n>ceil('28') in ceil('30') => False<n>ceil('28.1') in ceil('29.9') => True<n>ceil('280') < ceil('300') ```<n><n>### B: input: Freddy is calling His Family for New years eve.he calls his dad who lives in the same town as him and they talk for 50 min. then he calls his brother who lives on the other end

Choices:  A: sit B: being sociable C: talk D: drinking E: medium<n>Output:		A<n><n>Input: The total number of students that have applied for the scholarship are<n><n>Output: 408<n><n>Input: The number of students will be<n><n>Output: 11<n><n>#!/usr/bin/python3<n># -*- coding: utf-8 -*- <n># @Time  : 2020-06-28 17:23 <n># @Author : xinwen<n># @Email  : xinwen19970708@163.com<n># @Version : 1.0<n># @Package : <n># @Desc   :<n><n>'''<n>import math<n><n>class Solution:<n>    def multipleChoice(self, inputString):<n>        """<n>        :param inputString: Tapanga and Coley have 15 candy. However Coley have 3 more candy than Tapanga. How many candy does Tapanka have?<n>        :return: 12<n>        """<n>        count, left_candy, right_candy = 0, 0, 15<n>        while True:<n>            temp = math.floor(count / 6)<n>            if temp == count % 6:<n>                count -= temp<n>                break<n>            else:<n>                count -= count % 6<n>                left_candy += 15 // 6<n>                count = math.floor( (left_candy + right_candy) / 2 ) * 6 - count<n>                left_candies += 10 if left_candy >= 10 else 5<n>                right_candies += temp - left_candies<n>        return left_candies + right_candies - 2<n><n><n>def main():<n>    inputString = [<n>        'Tapanga and Corey together have 66 candys. Choices: 1) The use of tersely worded phrases that don't add any meaning. 2) A sentence or statement that cannot be denied. 3) A sentence or statement with two or more grammatically correct sentences. 4) A mathematical statement (i.e. in one form) with exactly two solutions. 5) A statement that is both false and true. 6) A sentence that is self-referential.<n>Output: A mathematical statement with exactly two solutions.<n><n>Input:In what ways could a tautology be used by a liar? Choices: The liar could 1) use a tautology (by writing two sentences that mean the same thing, and can't both be wrong). This will sound convincing and persuasive to the audience. The audience won't be able to refute the claim. 2) use a tautologous phrase ("as cold as the north pole"). This helps add details and create an image in the audience's mind. 3) write a sentence in the tautological format of "If a cow is a mammal, then a mammal is a cow." This could help avoid answering questions about the truth of the statement. 4) use a phrase like "A rose is a rose," which could be used as a riddle, but also could be used as an obfuscation. 5) use a phrase like  "All cats are mammals" in a statement like "All cats will die someday." 6) use a non-sequitur sentence, also known as "the tautological fallacy." <n>Output: 3 & 4.<n><n>Input:Mark your ______ so that no one can look at your math work. A class `InputFile` represents the input file itself, which contains an abstract class `Line` containing a member `contents`, that's a `std::string`, which contains the contents of a single line. A class `Inference` represents a single line that needs to be inferred, and can be thought of as the program itself. A class `State` represents a single state of the program, with a member `value`. The `inference` class takes references to the inference file, inference, state, and line classes to maintain state and the inference of the program. Inference classes can be thought of as a stack that has a "done" state and a state with an unknown state on top.<n><n>###<n><n>This problem uses the following input file:<n><n>```<n>1:10 20 20<n>35<n>```<n><n>### Instruction:Answer the Questions below.<n><n><n>1.What are the objects within `Inference`? Write their names and explain what they are in your words. For example, `Inference` is a `boost::scoped_ptr`. Remember that this problem does not use namespaces.<n><n>-Inference<n>  Inference is the main class of the program to make the decisions based on inputs<n><n><n>2.What is an `InputFile`? Write its name and its role. For example, `InputFile` is a boost::scoped_ptr initialized with a pointer to a `istream`. You shouldn't have to use any other libraries.<n><n>-InputFile<n>  An `InputFile` is an abstraction to the input file

WOOD TWIG BRANCH BARK PALM LEAF SHOOT TREE STUMP BUCKET GRASS STAIR STEP PLANT BLOOM<n>Output: PLAYGROUND<n><n>### Instructoins:What is one word that is synonym to both ODD and ROAMAN?<n><n>### Instictios:A word can be derived from a number according to its place in the English alphabet 1=A, 2=B, 3=C......, 14=N... 20 to 26 are letters with numbers assigned, 27=Q and so on. Given the sequence 84 1, 84234 6 and 8423154, find the missing numbers in between and the total sum of the numbers.<n><n>### The above number sequence is a permutation of the digit 8. The sequence is generated by taking the 1st digit of the number and assigning it 1, the 2nd 2, the 3rd 3, and so on until the sequence runs out or the number is all ones. What number should come next in the sequence?<n>Output<n>8415<n><n>### Insticions:

How many water jugs will the custodian fill with cups of water to provide the students with all the water they need in a day?<n>Output: 50<n><n>Input: It takes 1 hour for refrigerated dough to come to room temperature.  It takes 15 minutes to shape the dough and 2 hours to proof.  The bread takes 30 minutes to bake and 15 minutes to cool.  If the bakery opens at 6:00 am, what is the latest time the head baker can make it to the store to start working?<n>Output: 2<n><n>Input:What type of home is most likely to have an attic filled with historical items? Choices:  A: top of home B: older houses C: victorian house D: own home E: material<n>Output:		material<n><n># Solution<n><n>```python<n># Python program for Making Your Dental Office a Little Healthier<n><n>import sys<n><n>num_args = len(sys.argv)<n>if num_args!= 4:<n>    print 'Usage: python dental_office.py file1 file2 file3'<n>    sys.exit(1)<n><n>files = sys.argv[1:]<n><n>if not all(map(os.path.isfile, files)):<n>    for f in files:<n>        print 'File does not exist: ', f<n>    sys.exit(-1)<n><n>for f in files:<n>    contents = open(f).read().lower()<n>    for word in contents:<n>        if (word.isalpha()):<n>            if word.isupper():<n>                word = word.lower()<n>            if word not in words_per_person:<n>                words_per_person[word] = words_per_person.get(word, 0) + 1<n>    # Write out the counts to a dictionary<n>    fout = open(f+'.tally','w+')<n>    fout.write(' '.join(words)+ '\n')<n>    words_per_person_fout = fout<n>    fout.close()<n>```<n>

The houses on the street are generally divided up by lot size. The first time a house is sold or listed it sets the standard for the lot size of the house. The other aspects of the house influence the price: a big house on a large lot, a brand new house on a small lot, and an expensive house on a small lot are all rare, so the house is worth significantly more. Over time, the average size of houses and the average age of houses will be larger, and so a new house built on a big lot will be significantly more expensive than a big house on a small lot.  The price varies by lot size for houses that are all around the same age, because of supply and demand. If the bakery opens at 6:00 am, what is the latest time the head baker can make it to the store to start working?<n>Output: 2<n><n>Input:Where might a yard be tiny? Choices:  A: farmland B: neighborhood C: city D: property E: subdivision<n>Output:		Subdivision<n><n>### Answer:<n><n>### 1.	The candies have to be added.<n><n>$$Tapanga:8+45+50+15+2\Rightarrow66$$corey:6+21+31+0\Rightarrow29$$<n><n>### 2.	The dollar he spent for each call is calculated by its price.<n><n>$$\frac{1}{2}=5+\frac{1}{25}=5.5,$$$$5.5*8=47,$$$$47*1.5=70.5$$,$$70.5*1.6=114.2$$<n><n>###	3.	The total time is the sum of the days.<n><n>$$8+5.5+5.5+4.5+6.5$$<n><n>###4.	It is the number that was not sold.<n><n>$$800-60-20-4-10$$,$$\Rightarrow600$$<n><n>###5.	It is the total amount of money<n><n>$$\frac{{2\times22}}{{1+4}}+\frac{{2\times18}}{{1+4\quad+2}}\rightarrow$$,$$(22*2+12)\times 2=96,$$$54+94=148,$$2+12+12=26,$$148+26=174$$<n><n>###6.	The total of money from selling each dog is calculated.<n><n>$$\{(14)\times {3\over4}\times300\+(14)\times {5\over4}\times 100\}+\{(20)\times {3\times300\over4}\}+\{(10)\times {300\over3}+100\times {3\over 1}\}$$<n><n>$$(1\times 1\textrm{h}\times 3\times 3\textrm{h})+(1\times 2\textrm{h}\+2\times 3\times [1\times 12.5]\ \textrm{h})$$<n>$$2.5\textrm{h}$$<n><n>

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Tapanga and Corey have 66 candies together. However, Tapanga has 8 more candies than Corey. Cameron has 30 books and he donates a third of his books to the library. After donating their books, how many books in total do Boris and Cameron have together?<n>Output: 38<n><n>Input: There are 3 boxes of cereal. One box holds 14 ounces of cereal. How much cereal is there in all 3 cereal boxes?<n>Output: 33<n><n>Input: A jug needs 40 cups of water to be full. A custodian at Truman Elementary School has to fill water jugs for 200 students, who drink 10 cups of water in a day. How many water jugs will the custodian fill with cups of water to provide the students with all the water they need in a day?<n>Output: 50<n><n>Input: It takes 1 hour for refrigerated dough to come to room temperature.  It takes 15 minutes to shape the dough and 2 hours to proof.  The bread takes 30 minutes to bake and 15 minutes to cool.  If the bakery opens at 6:00 am, what is the latest time the head baker can make it to the store to start working?<n>Output: 2<n><n>Input:There are many cubicles in the office, they all have computers for employees to what? Choices:  A: teach B: cost money C: do work D: be productive E: help people<n>Output:		C<n><n>Input: At Taco Tuesdays, the price of tacos is half-price. If you buy the same number of tacos as the number at the top of your receipt, you will pay $0 total.<n>For example, if you buy 4 tacos, you will pay $2 after discount.<n><n>Input 4 or more: total cost after discount will be -$0 (i.e. total cost is $0)<n><n>Input 2 tacos: total cost after discout will be $1.60 (total cost is $1.60)<n><n>Input: 3: total cost after discnt will be $1.80 (total cost is -$0.10)<n><n>Input more than 3 tacos, including input 4: total cost after discunt will be -$0.30 (total cost is $$-0.30)$$.<n><n>Output: Total Cost after discount<n><n>Note: all input and output are in terms of positive numbers and the number of tacos is 2-digit<n>```<n><n># Solution:<n>We are going to use the method of Dynamic Programming in this question. <n>Dynamic Programming (DP) (sometimes D.P) as the name suggests is a programming method that uses recursion, memory and optimization to solve problems.<n><n>We can observe that the problem is divided into sub-problems wherein at every level of recursion, we are trying to figure out the minimum cost in terms of total tacos.<n><n>```python<n>def min_tacos(n):<n>        if n+1 in CACHE:<n>            return CACHE[n+1]<n>        cost=0<n>        result = 0<n>        if n+2>=10001:<n>             print('input is negative',n+2)<n>             return 0<n>        for n1 in range(1,n+2):<n>            if n1 in CACHE and not (n+1+n1 in CACHE):<n>                result=min_tacos(n+1)<n>                result+=n1<n>                cost=cost+result<n>                CACHE[n1]=cost<n>        CACHE[n]=cost<n>        return cost<n>```<n>Here, `n` represents the total number of t
